MAD = Median of absolute deviations

# Quick exercise 16.4
x <- c(11.6, -13.8, -15.2, -14.2, 31.6)
median_x <- median(x)
med_dev <- abs(x - median_x)
mad <- median(med_dev)
mad
## [1] 1.4
mad <- function(n){
  x <- -n:n
  median_x <- median(x)
  med_dev <- abs(x - median_x)
  mad <- median(med_dev)
  mad 
}

calc_sd <- function(n){
  x <- -n:n
  std <- sd(x)
  std
}

N = 100000
width = 1000
mads <- sapply(seq(1, N, width), mad)
sds <- sapply(seq(1, N, width), calc_sd)
plotdf <- data.frame(n = seq(1, N, width),
                     type = c(rep("mad", length(seq(1, N, width))), 
                              rep("sd", length(seq(1, N, width)))),
                     values = c(mads, sds))

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(data = plotdf,
       mapping = aes(x = n, y = values, color = type)) +
  geom_point()

Graph shows the standard deviation is more sensitive to larger observations and larger than MAD

Expected Value Rules

  • E(c) = c
  • E(cX) = cE(X)
  • E(c + X) = c + E(X)
  • E(X^2) = VAR(X) + (E(X))^2

Variance Rules

  • VAR(X) = E(X^2) - (E(X))^2
  • VAR(c) = 0
  • VAR(cX) = c^2VAR(X)

pmf <- data_frame(x = c(13.5, 15.9, 19.1),

# calculate CI for normal distribution with unknown variance means we need to use a t-distribution
xbar <- 195.3
n <- 18
s <- 16.7
left <- xbar - qt(0.975, df = n-1)*s/sqrt(n)
right <- xbar + qt(0.975, df = n-1)*s/sqrt(n)
paste0("We are 95% confident the population mean falls between:    [", left, ", ", right, "]")
## [1] "We are 95% confident the population mean falls between:    [186.995285378093, 203.604714621907]"

\[\begin{align} B = N(\mu_B = 250, \sigma_B^2 = 15) \end{align}\] \[\begin{align} W = N(\mu_W = ?, \sigma_W^2 = 5) \end{align}\] \[\begin{align} X = B + W \end{align}\] \[\begin{align} X = N(\mu_B + \mu_W, \sigma_b^2 + \sigma_w^2) \end{align}\]

# solve for the sample sd from the 95% CI
crit <- qt(0.975, df = 16-1)
xbar <- midpoint
n <- 16
sd <- (1.6 - xbar)*sqrt(n)/-crit

# calculate the 99% CI
crit <- qt(0.995, df = 16-1)
